1950-1959  
Top: Donald Knuth – Case Institute of Technology (B.S. 1960, M.S. 1960), Ph.D. Caltech 1963.  
Accomplishments: Created the first systematic analysis of algorithmic complexity; began the seven-volume “Art of Computer Programming” (first volume 1968).  
Career: Consultant to Burroughs, professor at Stanford 1968-present; invented TeX typesetting system.  
Runner-up: John Backus – Columbia M.S. 1949. Led the IBM team that produced FORTRAN (1957), the first widely-used high-level language; created BNF notation. IBM Fellow 1963-1991.

1960-1969  
Top: Dennis Ritchie – Harvard B.S. Physics 1963, Ph.D. Applied Math 1968.  
Accomplishments: Designed C language (1969-73) and co-created UNIX with Ken Thompson; 1998 U.S. National Medal of Technology.  
Career: Bell Labs 1967-2007; “K&R” book made C the systems-programming lingua franca.  
Runner-up: Ken Thompson – UC Berkeley B.S. 1965, M.S. 1966. Wrote first UNIX kernel in PDP-7 assembly; invented B language (predecessor to C). Distinguished Engineer at Bell Labs, later at Google.

1970-1979  
Top: Donald Knuth (second peak) – Caltech Ph.D. 1963.  
Accomplishments: Completed first three volumes of TAOCP (1973-81), invented TeX (1977) and literate programming.  
Career: Stanford Professor 1968-present; ACM Turing Award 1974.  
Runner-up: Brian Kernighan – Toronto B.A.Sc. 1964, Princeton Ph.D. 1969. Co-authored “The C Programming Language” (1978), AWK, AMPL; Bell Labs 1969-2000, Princeton professor since 2000.

1980-1989  
Top: Richard Stallman – Harvard B.A. 1974, MIT AI Lab hacker.  
Accomplishments: Launched GNU Project (1983), founded Free Software Foundation (1985), GPL license; wrote GNU Emacs, GNU Compiler Collection.  
Career: MIT AI Lab 1971-84, FSF president 1985-present; MacArthur Fellow 1990.  
Runner-up: Bjarne Stroustrup – Aarhus M.S. 1975, Cambridge Ph.D. 1979. Invented C++ at Bell Labs (1979-89); published “The C++ Programming Language” 1985.

1990-1999  
Top: Linus Torvalds – University of Helsinki M.S. 1996.  
Accomplishments: Released Linux kernel 0.01 (1991); spearheaded open-source development model used by millions of servers and Android.  
Career: Transmeta 1997-2003, Linux Foundation Fellow 2003-present.  
Runner-up: Tim Berners-Lee – Oxford Physics B.A. 1976. Wrote first web browser/server (1990), defined HTML/HTTP/URL; founded W3C at MIT 1994; knighted 2004.

2000-2009  
Top: Jeff Dean – Minnesota B.S. 1990, Washington Ph.D. 1996.  
Accomplishments: Co-designed Google File System, MapReduce, Bigtable; set early Google-scale performance records; ACM Fellow 2009.  
Career: DEC, Compaq, Google 1999-present (Google Senior Fellow).  
Runner-up: Sanjay Ghemawat – MIT B.S. 1987, Cornell Ph.D. 1990. Co-author of GFS, MapReduce, Bigtable; Google Senior Fellow; ACM Fellow 2009.

2010-2019  
Top: Jeff Dean (second peak) – same education.  
Accomplishments: Led TensorFlow (2015), Spanner globally-distributed database, Google Brain deep-learning advances; Turing Award 2018 (with Ghemawat & MapReduce team).  
Career: Google Senior Fellow, head of Google AI 2018-21.  
Runner-up: Chris Lattner – Portland State B.S. 2000, UIUC M.S. 2002. Created LLVM compiler, Clang, Swift language (Apple 2010-17); VP Tesla Autopilot, Google TensorFlow 2017-20.
